// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Effectful stages (RFC-0008 C4) - the liminal capability-injection model.
//
// A PURE stage (`stage`, `screen`) imports nothing but base WASI and is therefore
// deterministic by construction. An EFFECTFUL stage may import HOST-PROVIDED
// capabilities (a key-value store here; outbound HTTP in C5) - but only the ones
// the host GRANTS it at composition time, and the host refuses to load a component
// whose actual imports exceed its declared grant (checked from the component's
// imports alone, no code inspection). Its output is annotations only: it returns a
// batch the host records as annotation facts; it has no capability to write
// canonical entities (that would require a storage import the host never grants).
// Same batched-Arrow boundary as the pure stages.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// A host-owned key-value capability. A component granted `kv` can persist small
/// per-stage state (dedup markers, running counts, seen-before flags) across
/// batches. The host owns the store - its scope, size, and durability - so a
/// component cannot use it to escape the sandbox, only to remember.
interface kv {
    get: func(key: string) -> option<list<u8>>;
    set: func(key: string, value: list<u8>);
}

/// The effectful stage export: batch in (Arrow IPC), annotations out (Arrow IPC).
interface effectful {
    run: func(batch: list<u8>) -> result<list<u8>, string>;
}

/// A world for an effectful stage that needs the `kv` capability. The import is
/// what makes the capability requirement visible in the component's type - the
/// host reads it and refuses to instantiate unless `kv` was granted.
world effectful-kv {
    import kv;
    export effectful;
}
